You MUST sign up online. The classes fill up fast, so make sure you schedule in advance. The owner makes this clear every time you call; it's her first concern since that's the only way to guarantee you'll have a spot. You have to book at least a day in advance, so hit their website and reserve your spot!
Like the Prowess Pole Fitness Facebook page so you can see when they put on their "Cirque Saturday" events. It's like a dance recital, but in aerial form :O it's amazing!

ALWAYS sign up online for any class. This is how they know they aren't over booking since the large pole room only has 9 poles and the front room only has 3. Make sure you read the info for each class, this tells you who the instructor is, what to wear (very important!), and what time as well as room you'll meet in. Make sure you check an hour or two before the scheduled time online to see if the class may have been cancelled (this happens if no one signs up). Have fun! Ask lots of questions!

Before you post a negative review of this establishment, ask yourself whether your issue or complaint is valid and evidence-based, or if it's a personal problem--your own demons haunting you. 

If it's personal, don't project and tarnish Bowlero's reputation. Also, if you drank alcohol, ask yourself whether you're cogent, in a rational state of mind, and ultimately have the ability to make sound judgements, based on defined logical models. If not, please refrain from unnecessary commentary.

Remember, this is a bowling alley first; restaurant and bar, second. 

With that in mind, manage your expectations accordingly. 

You're not at a Michelin 3-star restaurant with a random bowling alley, so refrain from reviewing this establishment as such.

You're at a premier bowling alley that also offers decent fare and beverages to complete your experience, so I recommend you review this establishment thusly.

If you're interested in shopping or consigning, bear in mind that the price the buyer pays gets split 50\/50 with the store (standard consignment, from my experience consigning handmades). So if you're getting a $200 Tahari suit for $100, the original owner only gets $50 and the store only gets $50. This seems like a fair deal to me, but your mileage may vary.
